image.altText: Collage of baby, pink flowers, scallop shell, and butterfly on dark blue background with clouds in bottom third.

props.synopsis: There are no doctors, no hospitals, not even midwives. The women who subscribe say it's "empowering" and the only way to experience true childbirth. This is the world of freebirth.

title.children: Women are choosing 'freebirth' over hospital but no-one is counting the deaths

image.altText: A composite image showing influencer Tully Smyth.

props.synopsis: Testimonial promotion of regulated health services is illegal under Australia's advertising laws, but paid partnerships with influencers about egg freezing continue to appear on social media feeds, with the health regulator saying it is a "complex" legal area.

title.children: Fertility services are paying social media influencers to promote egg freezing — but is that legal?

image.altText: Ambulance rushing along a road with lights on

props.synopsis: Police are investigating reports a car left the road and rolled, killing all four inside.

title.children: Driver and three passengers dead after car rolls in northern NSW

image.altText: Illustration of murder victim Luke Davies, Jesse Baird and Beau Lamarre-Condon

props.synopsis: Some time between 12:01am and 5:30pm on Monday, Luke Davies and Jesse Baird were allegedly killed in Sydney. A police officer is behind bars after the week-long investigation, but more questions remain unanswered.

title.children: How police tracked down one of their own over the alleged murder of missing Sydney couple

image.altText: Court sketch of Snowtown accomplice Mark Ray Haydon sitting in the dock.

props.synopsis: The South Australian government will argue in court that bodies-in-the-barrels accomplice Mark Ray Haydon poses an "appreciable risk to the safety of the community if not supervised".

title.children: Snowtown accomplice Mark Haydon poses 'appreciable risk', court document alleges

image.altText: Krystal and Anastasia Marshall hug and smile.

props.synopsis: Anastasia Marshall applies for bail in the Adelaide Magistrates Court after being charged with murdering ex-wife Krystal Marshall in October.

title.children: Woman accused of murdering ex-wife Krystal Marshall applies for bail

image.altText: Dark clouds gather in the sky.

props.synopsis: Scorching end to summer expected for south-east as heavy rain falls on east and west coasts.

title.children: Return to La Niña in 2024 a strong possibility, latest modelling shows

image.altText: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu speaking at a podium with Israeli flags in the background.

props.synopsis: The document proposes Israel would maintain security control over all land west of Jordan, including the occupied West Bank and Gaza — territories where the Palestinians hope to establish an independent state.

title.children: Netanyahu unveils plan for post-war Gaza, saying Israel would keep security control on Palestinian areas

image.altText: A woman in exercise gear looks down a lonely stretch of road with trees on either side.

props.synopsis: Women in the missing Ballarat mother's hometown are either running in groups or not at all, and they're not alone in their fears — 90 per cent of women in a national running group say they joined for safety reasons.

title.children: Samantha Murphy's disappearance goes to the heart of women's fears about running alone

image.altText: Intuitive Machines' Nova-C Odysseus lander

title.children: NASA and US company give first press conference since historic Moon landing

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: How a technical issue was fixed on the fly
Odysseus is now believed to be lying sideways

image.altText: A military tank in camouflage print. There's a man in military uniform standing on it.

props.synopsis: Australia will be asked to consider donating its entire fleet of aging Abrams tanks to Ukraine as part of a broader package of military support that includes ammunition desperately needed in the war-torn country.

title.children: War-weary Ukraine shows renewed interest in Australia's aging Abrams tanks

image.altText: A crowd of people dance outside.

props.synopsis: For thousands of unlucky Swifties who couldn’t land tickets to the Eras tour, just being near their idol was — nearly — enough.

image.altText: A man holding a gun and looking at a camera

title.children: Having 'failed to make a breakthrough', Ukraine is entering a third year of war 'outgunned' and 'outmanned'

image.altText: A graphic showing a middle aged white man, a younger man white and a fair-skinned Aboriginal woman

props.synopsis: The ABC has recently heard hundreds of stories from Australians with disability about their experiences with transport across the country. Advocates say systems are failing them.

title.children: These horror stories show how transport systems 'fail' Australians with disability

image.altText: Anthony Albanese at Woolworths

props.synopsis: Faced with mounting public anger about big corporates and the cost of living, can the government create a big enough bang to convince consumers it is serious?

title.children: The government is picking fights on prices for consumers, but can it land a punch?

image.altText: A man dressed in a suit and a woman dressed in a white suit stand on a balcony next to a scenic view of the ocean.

props.synopsis: When Italy became a republic, its former monarchs were forced into exile. In the decades since, two branches of the family have been locked in a squabble over who is the rightful ruler to Italy's non-existent throne.

title.children: With the son of Italy's last king dead, a decades-long battle over a defunct crown is laid bare

image.altText: A person wheels their trolley past the end of a supermarket aisle. They are blurred from the motion and are not identifiable.

props.synopsis: The fight to pay a fair price for food has become one of the most divisive at a time of seemingly countless divisive debates, writes Virginia Trioli.

title.children: We already know the solutions to our super-sized supermarket problem — but there are six inquiries underway

image.altText: Four people in black suits stand around a recently dug grave which is yet to be filled in with dirt

image.altText: Composit pygmy possum and reef

image.altText: A composite image of Beau Lamarre, Luke Davies and Jesse Baird

image.altText: A large cloud of smoke rises in the distance

image.altText: An artfully put together red, black and white graphic depicts a group of students walking down a university hallway.

props.synopsis: State, territory and federal education ministers have agreed to a national action plan to tackle sexual assault on university campuses, with student activists labelling the suite of reforms groundbreaking and transformative.

title.children: National plan to reduce sexual violence at universities to be implemented

image.altText: A close-up of a smartphone displaying an Nvidia logo, sandwiched between two computer parts.

title.children: 'They are literally printing money on silicon': AI sends Nvidia's market value soaring higher than Australia's GDP

image.altText: A composite image of Donald Trump, Shane Gillis and Elon Musk

title.children: Comedian Shane Gillis was fired by Saturday Night Live in 2019. So why is he returning this weekend to host?

image.altText: Adam Zampa smiles and hugs Matt Wade as teammates celebrate with them

image.altText: close up of a young woman's face

image.altText: two young school boys walk to school wearing backpacks as one puts his arm around the others shoulder

title.children: Private schools building 'office towers and Scottish castles' while public schools left with demountable classrooms, union says

image.altText: An aerial view of a Sydney-to-Melbourne train that derailed near Wallan on February 20, 2020.

title.children: Train companies admit safety failures in deadly derailment near Melbourne

image.altText: A man walks out of the doors of the ACT law courts.

title.children: 'Charismatic leader' avoids jail over Canberra protests that saw doors to Old Parliament House set alight

image.altText: A close up of a young girl wearing a pink jumper standing in front of rubble.

title.children: As famine grips Gaza, this family experiences stomach cramps after a meal of animal feed and sticks

image.altText: Sandra Huller in German braids holds a baby in a garden

props.synopsis: Loosely based on a 2014 novel, this film is set in a family home next to Auschwitz during WWII. But instead of being deeply emotional, this film is icy cold — which is, somehow, all the more threatening.
